did.abstract: Henry William Hofstetter was a professor of optometry from 1952 until his retirement in 1980. He served as director of the Division of Optometry 1952-1970. Collection consists publications, personal and professional correspondence, records regarding Prof. Hofstetter's community and professional service, and files related to his research.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for research. Advance notice required.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Henry William Hofstetter, Rudy Professor Emeritus of Optometry, was born in Windsor Mills, Ohio in 1914. He earned three degrees from Ohio State University: a B.S. in Optometry in 1939, and his M.S. and Ph.D. in Physiological Optics in 1940 and 1942. He was awarded several honorary degrees, including an O.D. from the Los Angeles College of Optometry in 1954.

Hofstetter arrived at Indiana University in 1952 to assume the directorship of the newly created Division of Optometry. He held this post until 1970, when he resigned from his administrative duties. Hofstetter remained an active member of the faculty, receiving the Rudy Professorship in 1974. He retired from his academic position in 1979 and was awarded the title Rudy Professor Emeritus by the Board of Trustees. Over the course of his career, Hofstetter wrote, co-authored, or edited more than 400 works, including four editions of the Dictionary of Visual Science, and Optometry: Professional, Economic, and Legal Aspects, which became the standard text on the subject.
Hofstetter died on May 10, 2002 in Bloomington, Indiana.

arrangement.head: Arrangement/Organization
arrangement.p: Organized in four series: Biographical and family, Correspondence, Service, and Research.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: The Hofstetter collection is organized in four series: Biographical and Family, Correspondence, Service, and Research.

Biographical and Family: This series consists of four folders, as well as the book Our Huntsburg Heritage (1963). It contains newspaper and magazine articles and several small booklets written about Hofstetter and his family, dating from 1953 to 1991. Also in this series is a typescript diary kept by Hofstetter from 1995 to 1996 and one folder of his non-research related writings.

Correspondence: The largest series in the collection, consisting of 617 folders, this series contains Hofstetter's incoming and outgoing correspondence. It is arranged alphabetically by author or recipient's last name, and chronologically within each folder. A number of folders also contain photos of Hofstetter at conferences, or of his colleagues and family members. Dates for this series range from 1952 to 1997, but the bulk of the material falls between 1980 and 1995. The series includes both professional and personal letters.

Service: Consisting of 19 folders, this series contains material relating to Hofstetter's community and professional service. The folders are arranged by subject, and cover dates from 1953 to 1990. An active member of the Bloomington Rotary, he gave numerous brief talks as well as editing the club's newsletter, both of which are included in this series. Agenda and minutes for the Board of Directors of the IU Y.M.C.A. and the IU Science Advisory Committee, of which Hofstetter was a member, are also included. Of special interest are documents relating to his tenure as Director of the School of Optometry, such as his annual reports to the President of the University and his annual letter to the optometry faculty.

Research: The Research series hold 44 folders and eight bound volumes, dating from 1941 to 1997 and arranged chronologically. Included are notes and manuscripts from several of his research projects, and grant proposals which describe his research. The series also contains two copies of his many published articles and one copy of each of his books. Of interest is a copy of his 1942 doctoral dissertation in which Hofstetter pencilled corrections and changes.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Material
separatedmaterial.p: Photographs transferred to the University Archives Photographs Collection.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material
relatedmaterial.p: Researchers may also wish to consult the International Library, Archives, and Museum of Optometry in St. Louis, as Dr. Hofstetter donated many of his optometry related papers to that institution.
